05152nmm a2200985Ia 9781479868926DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798689267 a10.18574/nyu/9781479868926.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)681050  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0310002bisacsh1 aReckson, Lindsay V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRealist Ecstasy :bReligion, Race, and Performance in American Literature /cLindsay V. Reckson. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b22 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerformance and American Cultures ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Being Beside -- t1. Reconstructing Secularisms -- t2. Archival Enthusiasm -- t3. The Ghost Dance and Realism’s Techno- Spiritual Frontier -- t4. Touching a Button -- t5. Born, Again -- tCoda: Behind, Before, Beside -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHonorable Mention, Barnard Hewitt Award from the American Society for Theater ResearchExplores the intersection and history of American literary realism and the performance of spiritual and racial embodiment. Recovering a series of ecstatic performances in late nineteenth- and early twentieth-century American realism, Realist Ecstasy travels from camp meetings to Native American ghost dances to storefront church revivals to explore realism’s relationship to spiritual experience. In her approach to realism as both an unruly archive of performance and a wide-ranging repertoire of media practices—including literature, photography, audio recording, and early film—Lindsay V. Reckson argues that the real was repetitively enacted and reenacted through bodily practice. Realist Ecstasy demonstrates how the realist imagining of possessed bodies helped construct and naturalize racial difference, while excavating the complex, shifting, and dynamic possibilities embedded in ecstatic performance: its production of new and immanent forms of being beside. Across her readings of Stephen Crane, James Weldon Johnson, and Nella Larsen, among others, Reckson triangulates secularism, realism, and racial formation in the post-Reconstruction moment. Realist Ecstasy shows how post-Reconstruction realist texts mobilized gestures—especially the gestures associated with religious ecstasy—to racialize secularism itself. Reckson offers us a distinctly new vision of American realism as a performative practice, a sustained account of how performance lives in and through literary archives, and a rich sense of how closely secularization and racialization were linked in Jim Crow America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aAnna Julia Cooper.  aFrances E. W. Harper.  aGhost Dance.  aHamlin Garland.  aJames Mooney.  aJames Weldon Johnson.  aJim Crow.  aNella Larsen.  aPentecostalism.  aReconstruction.  aW. E. B. Du Bois.  aWilliam Dean Howells.  aWilliam Van der Weyde.  aaffect.  abody.  acapital punishment.  aconversion.  aelectricity.  aethnography.  agesture.  ahaunting.  aintersectionality.  alynching.  amessiah craze.  aperformance.  aphotography.  aqueerness.  arealism.  arecording.  areenactment.  asecularism.  asecularization.  asettler colonialism.  asexuality.  astorefront church.  atemporality.  awhiteness.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479868926.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479868926423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97814798689